INN Hotels Project¶

Context¶

A significant number of hotel bookings are called-off due to cancellations or no-shows. The typical reasons for cancellations include change of plans, scheduling conflicts, etc. This is often made easier by the option to do so free of charge or preferably at a low cost which is beneficial to hotel guests but it is a less desirable and possibly revenue-diminishing factor for hotels to deal with. Such losses are particularly high on last-minute cancellations.

The new technologies involving online booking channels have dramatically changed customers’ booking possibilities and behavior. This adds a further dimension to the challenge of how hotels handle cancellations, which are no longer limited to traditional booking and guest characteristics.

The cancellation of bookings impact a hotel on various fronts:

  • Loss of resources (revenue) when the hotel cannot resell the room.
  • Additional costs of distribution channels by increasing commissions or paying for publicity to help sell these rooms.
  • Lowering prices last minute, so the hotel can resell a room, resulting in reducing the profit margin.
  • Human resources to make arrangements for the guests.

Objective¶

The increasing number of cancellations calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in predicting which booking is likely to be canceled. INN Hotels Group has a chain of hotels in Portugal, they are facing problems with the high number of booking cancellations and have reached out to your firm for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist have to analyze the data provided to find which factors have a high influence on booking cancellations, build a predictive model that can predict which booking is going to be canceled in advance, and help in formulating profitable policies for cancellations and refunds.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of customers' booking details. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • Booking_ID: unique identifier of each booking
  • no_of_adults: Number of adults
  • no_of_children: Number of Children
  • no_of_weekend_nights: Number of weekend nights (Saturday or Sunday) the guest stayed or booked to stay at the hotel
  • no_of_week_nights: Number of week nights (Monday to Friday) the guest stayed or booked to stay at the hotel
  • type_of_meal_plan: Type of meal plan booked by the customer:
    • Not Selected – No meal plan selected
    • Meal Plan 1 – Breakfast
    • Meal Plan 2 – Half board (breakfast and one other meal)
    • Meal Plan 3 – Full board (breakfast, lunch, and dinner)
  • required_car_parking_space: Does the customer require a car parking space? (0 - No, 1- Yes)
  • room_type_reserved: Type of room reserved by the customer. The values are ciphered (encoded) by INN Hotels.
  • lead_time: Number of days between the date of booking and the arrival date
  • arrival_year: Year of arrival date
  • arrival_month: Month of arrival date
  • arrival_date: Date of the month
  • market_segment_type: Market segment designation.
  • repeated_guest: Is the customer a repeated guest? (0 - No, 1- Yes)
  • no_of_previous_cancellations: Number of previous bookings that were canceled by the customer prior to the current booking
  • no_of_previous_bookings_not_canceled: Number of previous bookings not canceled by the customer prior to the current booking
  • avg_price_per_room: Average price per day of the reservation; prices of the rooms are dynamic. (in euros)
  • no_of_special_requests: Total number of special requests made by the customer (e.g. high floor, view from the room, etc)
  • booking_status: Flag indicating if the booking was canceled or not.

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=True, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot
In [27]:
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()
In [28]:
def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

### function to plot distributions wrt target


def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using statsmodels
def model_performance_classification_statsmodels(
    model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5
):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """

    # checking which probabilities are greater than threshold
    pred_temp = model.predict(predictors) > threshold
    # rounding off the above values to get classes
    pred = np.round(pred_temp)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [94]:
# defining a function to plot the confusion_matrix of a classification model


def confusion_matrix_statsmodels(model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors) > threshold
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Observations: The accuracy of 80% indicates the model performs well. So, 80.75% of the predictions made by the model on the training data were correct. However, accuracy alone might not provide a complete picture, especially in the case of imbalanced datasets.

The recall of 64% is abit low so there is room for improvement in correctly identifying positive cases. So Recall (also known as sensitivity) measures the proportion of actual positive cases that were correctly identified by the model. A recall of 0.64443 indicates that roughly 64.44% of the positive cases in the training data were correctly identified by the model.

With precision of 73.5% the model is relatively reliable though not too good. So Precision measures the proportion of positive predictions made by the model that were actually correct. A precision of 0.73519 suggests that around 73.52% of the instances predicted as positive by the model were indeed true positives.

F1 score of 0.687 indicates averall performance of model and reflects a balance between precision and recall.

In [109]:
# we will define a function to check VIF
def checking_vif(predictors):
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["feature"] = predictors.columns

    # calculating VIF for each feature
    vif["VIF"] = [
        variance_inflation_factor(predictors.values, i)
        for i in range(len(predictors.columns))
    ]
    return vif

# initial list of columns
cols = X_train.columns.tolist()

# setting an initial max p-value
max_p_value = 1

while len(cols) > 0:
    # defining the train set
    x_train_aux = X_train[cols]

    # fitting the model
    model = sm.Logit(y_train, x_train_aux.astype(float)).fit(disp=False)

    # getting the p-values and the maximum p-value
    p_values = model.pvalues
    max_p_value = max(p_values)

    # name of the variable with maximum p-value
    feature_with_p_max = p_values.idxmax()

    if max_p_value > 0.05:
        cols.remove(feature_with_p_max)
    else:
        break
    selected_features = cols
print(selected_features)

All p-values are less than 0.05. Intercept (-944.1830): This is the baseline log-odds of the event occurring when all predictor variables are set to zero.

Coefficients for Predictor Variables: Each coefficient represents the change in the log-odds of the event occurring associated with a one-unit change in the corresponding predictor variable, holding all other variables constant. For example:

A one-unit increase in no_of_weekend_nights is associated with a 0.1576 increase in the log-odds of the event occurring, all else being equal. A one-unit increase in required_car_parking_space is associated with a decrease of 1.6112 in the log-odds of the event occurring, all else being equal. Positive coefficients indicate that as the predictor variable increases, the log-odds of the event occurring also increase, and vice versa for negative coefficients.

Predictor Variables: Each predictor variable included in the equation contributes to the prediction of the event occurring. The equation incorporates various predictor variables such as no_of_week_nights, lead_time, arrival_year, type_of_meal_plan_Not Selected, room_type_reserved_Room_Type 7, market_segment_type_Offline, and others.

Converting coefficients to odds¶

The coefficients of the logistic regression model are in terms of log(odd), to find the odds we have to take the exponential of the coefficients. Therefore, odds = exp(b) The percentage change in odds is given as odds = (exp(b) - 1) * 100

In [116]:

# finding the percentage change
perc_change_odds = (np.exp(lg1.params) - 1) * 100

Odds: These are the odds ratios associated with each feature in the logistic regression model. They indicate the change in the odds of the target variable for a one-unit change in the predictor variable, holding all other variables constant. for example: Number of weekend nights: Holding all other features constant a unit change in Number of weekend nights will increase the odds of a booking being cancelled by 1.17 times or a 17.07% increase in odds.

Change_odd%: This represents the percentage change in the odds ratio for each unit change in the corresponding feature. It shows the impact of each feature on the odds of the target variable.

A feature with an odds ratio greater than 1 suggests that an increase in that feature's value is associated with higher odds of the target variable (e.g., odds ratio of 1.17 for no_of_weekend_nights suggests that for each additional weekend night, the odds of the target variable increase by approximately 17.07%). Conversely, a feature with an odds ratio less than 1 implies that an increase in that feature's value is associated with lower odds of the target variable (e.g., odds ratio of 0.19965 for required_car_parking_space suggests that for each additional required parking space, the odds of the target variable decrease by approximately 80.04%). The Change_odd% column provides insight into the sensitivity of the odds ratio to changes in the predictor variable. Positive percentages indicate an increase in odds with an increase in the feature, while negative percentages suggest a decrease in odds. For instance, a feature with a large positive percentage change in odds (e.g., arrival_month_2 with a change of 2098.7%) indicates a significant increase in odds with each unit change in that feature. Conversely, a large negative percentage change (e.g., no_of_weekend_nights with a change of -100%) suggests a substantial decrease in odds with each unit change in that feature.

def confusion_matrix_statsmodels(model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors) > threshold
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

def plot_prec_recall_vs_tresh(precisions, recalls, thresholds):
    plt.plot(thresholds, precisions[:-1], "b--", label="precision")
    plt.plot(thresholds, recalls[:-1], "g--", label="recall")
    plt.xlabel("Threshold")
    plt.legend(loc="upper left")
    plt.ylim([0, 1])


plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))

plt.show()

Final Model Summary¶

All the models are giving a generalized performance on training and test set. The highest recall is 82.6% on the traing set. Using the model with default threshold the model will give a lower recall and F1 score but good precision (73.4%) and accuracy (80.6%) scores - This model will only predict correctly on 64% of the booking cancellation cases so might help the hotel save resources but lose on potential bookings. Using the model with 0.42 threshold the model will give a lower recall than at 0.36 threshold but not too low precision and high accuracy scores - This model will help the hotel identify potential cancellations effectively but the cost of resources will be high. Using the model with 0.36 threshold the model will give a balance recall and precision score - This model will help the hotel to maintain a balance in predicting bookings likely to be cancelled and the cost of resources.

From the logistic regression model we identified that various predictor variables such as no_of_week_nights, lead_time, arrival_year, type_of_meal_plan_Not Selected, room_type_reserved_Room_Type 7, market_segment_type_Offline, and others are significant predictors of potential booking cancellations.

Number_of_weekend_nights: This variable has a coefficient of 0.1576, indicating that an increase in the number of weekend nights positively influences the predicted log-odds of the event occurring.

Required_car_parking_space: This variable has a coefficient of -1.6112, suggesting that requiring car parking space negatively impacts the predicted log-odds of the event occurring.

Lead_time: With a coefficient of 0.0162, lead time positively affects the predicted log-odds of the event occurring.

Arrival_year: This variable has a coefficient of 0.4651, indicating a positive influence on the predicted log-odds of the event occurring.

Repeated_guest: Although not listed explicitly in the equation, if this variable is binary (indicating whether the guest is a repeated visitor), the coefficient of -3.1509 suggests that being a repeated guest negatively affects the predicted log-odds of the event occurring.

no_of_previous_cancellations: With a coefficient of 0.3843, this variable positively impacts the predicted log-odds of the event occurring.

avg_price_per_room: This variable has a coefficient of 0.0188, indicating a positive influence on the predicted log-odds of the event occurring.

no_of_special_requests: With a coefficient of -1.5475, an increase in the number of special requests negatively affects the predicted log-odds of the event occurring.

market_segment_type_Offline: This variable has a coefficient of -1.8257, suggesting that bookings made through offline market segments have a negative impact on the predicted log-odds of the event occurring.

In conclusion: The logistic regression equation reveals several key variables that significantly influence the predicted probability of the event occurring. These variables include:

Number_of_weekend_nights: More weekend nights booked tend to increase the likelihood of the event occurring. Required_car_parking_space: Requiring car parking space decreases the likelihood of the event occurring. Lead_time: Longer lead times positively impact the likelihood of the event occurring. Arrival_year: Bookings in later years positively influence the likelihood of the event occurring. Repeated_guest: Being a repeated guest negatively affects the likelihood of the event occurring. Number_of_previous_cancellations: Previous cancellations positively affect the likelihood of the event occurring. Average price_per_room: Higher average prices per room tend to increase the likelihood of the event occurring. Number_of_special_requests: More special requests decrease the likelihood of the event occurring.

Market_segment_type_Offline: Bookings made through offline market segments negatively impact the likelihood of the event occurring.

We create functions to calculate different metrics and confusion matrix so that we don't have to use the same code repeatedly for each model. The model_performance_classification_sklearn function will be used to check the model performance of models. The confusion_matrix_sklearnfunction will be used to plot the confusion matrix.

In [157]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [158]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Pre-Pruning¶

In [165]:
# Choose the type of classifier.
estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, class_weight="balanced")

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {
    "max_depth": np.arange(2, 7, 2),
    "max_leaf_nodes": [50, 75, 150, 250],
    "min_samples_split": [10, 30, 50, 70],
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
acc_scorer = make_scorer(f1_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimator, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer, cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
estimator = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

Next, we train a decision tree using effective alphas. The last value in ccp_alphas is the alpha value that prunes the whole tree, leaving the tree, clfs[-1], with one node.

In [175]:
clfs = []
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(
        random_state=1, ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha, class_weight="balanced"
    )
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    clfs.append(clf)
print(
    "Number of nodes in the last tree is: {} with ccp_alpha: {}".format(
        clfs[-1].tree_.node_count, ccp_alphas[-1]
    )
)

Number of nodes in the last tree is: 1 with ccp_alpha: 0.08117914389136943

f1_train = []

for clf in clfs:

    values_test = f1_score(y_test, pred_test)
    f1_test.append(values_test)

Model Performance Comparison and Conclusions¶

Decision tree models with pre-pruning and post-pruning both are giving equally high recall scores on both training and test sets. However, we will choose the post pruned tree as the best model since it is giving a slightly high precision score on the train and test sets than the pre-pruned tree.

Training Performance Comparison Accuracy: The Decision Tree sklearn and Decision Tree with Post-Pruning models achieve the same accuracy of 0.90005, while the Decision Tree with Pre-Pruning achieves a significantly higher accuracy of 0.99421. Accuracy measures the proportion of correctly classified instances out of the total instances in the training set.

Recall: The Decision Tree sklearn and Decision Tree with Post-Pruning models achieve the same recall of 0.90350, while the Decision Tree with Pre-Pruning achieves a slightly lower recall of 0.98661. Recall, also known as sensitivity, measures the proportion of actual positive instances that were correctly identified by the model.

Precision: The Decision Tree sklearn and Decision Tree with Post-Pruning models achieve the same precision of 0.81361, while the Decision Tree with Pre-Pruning achieves a higher precision of 0.99578. Precision measures the proportion of correctly predicted positive instances out of all instances predicted as positive.

F1 Score: The Decision Tree sklearn and Decision Tree with Post-Pruning models achieve the same F1 score of 0.85620, while the Decision Tree with Pre-Pruning achieves a slightly higher F1 score of 0.99117. The F1 score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall, providing a balance between these two metrics.

Testing Performance Comparison:

Accuracy: All three models achieve similar accuracy on the testing set, with the Decision Tree sklearn and Decision Tree with Pre-Pruning models both achieving an accuracy of 0.87108, and the Decision Tree with Post-Pruning model achieving a slightly lower accuracy of 0.86869.

Recall: The Decision Tree sklearn and Decision Tree with Pre-Pruning models achieve the same recall of 0.81034, while the Decision Tree with Post-Pruning model achieves a slightly higher recall of 0.85576.

Precision: The Decision Tree sklearn and Decision Tree with Pre-Pruning models achieve the same precision of 0.79521, while the Decision Tree with Post-Pruning model achieves a slightly lower precision of 0.76595.

F1 Score: The F1 scores for all three models on the testing set are relatively similar, with the Decision Tree sklearn and Decision Tree with Pre-Pruning models both achieving an F1 score of 0.80270, and the Decision Tree with Post-Pruning model achieving a slightly higher F1 score of 0.8083.

In summary, the Decision Tree with Pre-Pruning shows superior performance in terms of accuracy, recall, precision, and F1 score on the training set, indicating potential overfitting. However, on the testing set, all three models perform similarly, with the Decision Tree with Post-Pruning demonstrating slightly better recall and F1 score. This suggests that post-pruning helps generalize the model better to unseen data by reducing overfitting.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

  • What profitable policies for cancellations and refunds can the hotel adopt?
  • What other recommedations would you suggest to the hotel?

To address cancellations and refunds effectively and maximize profitability, the hotel can adopt several policies and implement additional strategies:

Flexible cancellation policies: Offer flexible cancellation policies that provide guests with options to modify or cancel their bookings with minimal penalties. Implementing policies such as free cancellation within a certain timeframe (e.g., 24 hours before check-in) can attract more bookings while reducing the likelihood of cancellations closer to the arrival date.

Tiered pricing and non-refundable rates: Implement tiered pricing structures that offer discounted rates for non-refundable bookings. This encourages guests to commit to their reservations while providing an incentive for booking in advance. Non-refundable rates can help mitigate revenue loss from cancellations by securing guaranteed revenue for the hotel.

Partial deposits or prepayments: Require guests to pay a partial deposit or prepayment at the time of booking, especially for high-demand periods or special promotions. Collecting a portion of the payment upfront reduces the financial impact of last-minute cancellations and ensures a level of commitment from guests.

Waitlist management: Implement a waitlist management system to fill canceled rooms quickly. Notify guests on the waitlist of available rooms and offer them the opportunity to book at a discounted rate. This maximizes occupancy and minimizes revenue loss from cancellations by optimizing room utilization.

Dynamic pricing and revenue management: Utilize dynamic pricing and revenue management strategies to adjust room rates based on demand fluctuations and booking patterns. Implement automated pricing algorithms that optimize rates in real-time to maximize revenue and profitability while considering factors such as seasonality, occupancy levels, and competitor pricing.

Upselling and cross-Selling: Offer upselling and cross-selling opportunities to increase revenue per guest. Promote room upgrades, amenities, and add-on services during the booking process or at check-in to enhance the guest experience and generate additional revenue streams.

Customer relationship management (CRM): Implement a CRM system to track guest preferences, booking history, and behavior patterns. Leverage guest data to personalize marketing communications, tailor offers to individual preferences, and foster guest loyalty. Building strong relationships with repeat guests can lead to higher retention rates and increased revenue over time.

Cancellation insurance: Offer guests the option to purchase cancellation insurance at the time of booking. Cancellation insurance provides guests with peace of mind and coverage for unforeseen circumstances that may lead to cancellations. Partnering with reputable insurance providers can generate additional revenue for the hotel while minimizing financial risk.

Post-stay feedback and Reputation Management: Solicit feedback from guests post-stay to identify areas for improvement and address any concerns promptly. Monitor online reviews and respond proactively to guest feedback to maintain a positive reputation and attract future bookings. Positive reviews and ratings can influence booking decisions and drive revenue growth.

Cost optimization and operational efficiency: Continuously evaluate operational processes and identify opportunities to streamline operations and reduce costs. Implement efficiency measures such as energy-saving initiatives, waste reduction programs, and optimized staffing levels to improve profitability while maintaining service quality.

By implementing these policies and recommendations, the hotel can effectively manage cancellations and refunds, optimize revenue generation, and enhance overall profitability. Additionally, fostering a guest-centric approach and prioritizing customer satisfaction can contribute to long-term success and sustained business growth.
